Most people rightfully horrified at his death have also been shielded from seeing the most disturbing Gaza footage. It's normal for people to have a strong psychological reaction to seeing the terrible murder of a familiar public figure. You don't have to choose one or the other.

In the end I am not here to tell people what to think, but it's been known for a long time that mass murder turns into statistics, while individual cases of tragedy can be far more moving for some people, because it's easier to comprehend them. There's no need to compare the two.
